metadata.name: Reblend #73
metadata.description:
There are two creative features to this project.
The first feature is related to the production of colors at random points, so that geometric shapes are placed in proper harmony with each other and then allowed to process and produce colors at the intersection.
The second feature is the subtraction of a part of the shapes that are located in the center, and in the place of subtraction, geometric shapes are replaced, which will produce a new content of regular geometric shapes.
This innovative art not only challenges the traditional concepts of beauty but also encourages the thinking of viewers to combine colors and geometric shapes.

S = Save
Made by p5.js

metadata.name: Gravity's End #231
metadata.description:
Gravity's End depicts fictional worlds being warped, distorted, and in rare cases, shattered, due to extreme gravitational forces.

Gravity's End is written with shaders, so a gpu is recommended. It is very gpu friendly, in that only one frame is rendered.

Rarities

- 21 palettes with 5 rare palettes (4% chance for rare).
- 10% chance of getting a shattered world.

Keys: 

's' saves a png in the exact size of the screen.

metadata.name: MOMENT #238
metadata.description:
An endless row of them making up each life. Some poignant, some inspiring, some grievous, some affirming - but most of them a tad boring, a bit generic, almost forgettable like bland fabric. How can a life constructed from such mundanity count for anything? Maybe thanks to the last one, the one that stitches them all together, like a punchline to an absurdist joke.

Generative art written in JavaScript + Canvas with a little bit of help from p5.js.

metadata.name: pendula #103
metadata.description: A grid of 17x17 chaotic pendulums. Each pendulum consists of 17 layers, each following a different, randomly generated square shaped route. We draw different shapes and colors at the end of each pendulum, as all 17 layers do a full lap simultaneously.

metadata.name: Crypt-o-Show #6
metadata.description:
Crypt-o-show is a parody art gallery generator, inspired by a very disappointing and comical NFT show produced by Christies. The infamous show displayed Artblock works on unsuitable screens, installed closely together, over a large squiggle on the wall. The generator creates a little gallery with a random selection of artworks that parody AB pieces – these are used as features in this work – forming a mini collection of collectibles. 

Crypt-o-show is a form of ‘institutional critique’ through generative art, and about generative art, poking fun at the both the market for on-chain generative artwork collections made addictive through their lottery mechanics, as well as mocking the traditional auction house and its blundering and inelegant support for these new digital practices. 

"The saddest thing you'll see today is, once again, brought to you by Christie's."
- @MPtherealmvp (twitter.com/MPtherealmvp/status/1442917552871526401)

Initial idea tweeted on 2/9/21 (twitter.com/M_PF/status/1443129233472212992)

metadata.name: The Managed Miles - part 1 #216
metadata.description:
A bespoke literary chance machine, crafted from a matrix of ranked, hand-crafted options.
The style and tone of the generated output influences the title, to match the poem as closely as possible.

Based on an original poem in four verses. This is part 1 (plus title). 
Parts 2-4 releasing concurrently.

The algorithm that drives the poem is an evolving feature map. Each word has a series of features that, when selected, contribute to the selection of the following words.

In this way, the poem evolves in a way that is deterministic but with very random roots. 

The chance of two transactions generating the same poem from the system is about 1 in 450,000.

Wily Guys [ T : @guyswily / W : wilyguys.com / I : @wilyguys / M : wilyguys.medium.com ] 
Liam Egan [ T : @neuromantic6 / W : github.com/liamegan / I : @liamgegan ]

metadata.name: RADII #64
Gold in Your Eyes #36
metadata.description:
This piece came to be as an adaptation of a workflow developed for an earlier Blender series, DeVoids.

The idea behind this technique is, instead of trying to create an image that fits to the needs, to modify and distort the UV Mapping of a 3d model.

UV Maps are usually though of as a needed step in creating a 3d asset, where you must achieve minimal distortion and minimize area losses. This piece explores narrative possibilities by ressignifying the tool usage.

Made in Cables.gl

metadata.name: Meander River Plot v1 #97
metadata.description:
A river meandering over a noise-based landscape. A line is drawn either horizontally, vertically, or more rarely, a ring. Time progresses for 1,000 iterations as the line travels, bends, and splits. 

There is a lot of variation on the line quality - from thin and controlled, to chunky and chaotic. It's a lot of fun to watch it run and see where it ends up.

I've been experimenting with this algorithm for a long time and this is the most visually interesting variation so far.
